description.plain:
David Burd, better known as “Lil Dicky”, is an American Jewish rapper who was born and raised in Cheltenham, a small suburb of Philadelphia. He first attracted attention through his viral song/video “Ex-Boyfriend,” which gained over a million views the first day it was uploaded. The song was featured on his very successful debut mixtape entitled So Hard.

His debut album Professional Rapper was released on July 31, 2015.
The album debuted as the Number One Rap Album, Number One Comedy Album, Number One Independent Album, and Number One Digital Album on the Billboard charts, and Number One overall on iTunes.

Since then, he has gone on to win the People’s Choice Webby Award for Best Online Film and Video: Music Video, and was chosen as one of XXL’s Freshman Class 2016, following in the footsteps of prior “class members” such as Kendrick Lamar, Wiz Khalifa, and many others.

description.plain:
“Freaky Friday” is a song that involves a crossover between Lil Dicky and Chris Brown.

The first verse is Lil Dicky speaking as Chris Brown and the second verse is Chris Brown living as Lil Dicky. Both artists choose different things to take advantage of while living the other person’s life.

The song is a nod to the movie Freaky Friday that was released in 1976 and remade in 2003. The movie created this premise where a girl and her mother switch places in order to experience each other’s lives.

Lil Dicky released the music video on his 30th birthday, which gave him high hopes for its success.

description.plain:
“Earth” is an environmental awareness song, released three days before Earth Day in 2019, about the dangers that climate change has on our planet and its ecosystems.

During an interview on The Ellen Show, Lil Dicky revealed the track features over 30 artists, with each of them taking on the roles of a different animal. For example, Justin Bieber plays on the role of a baboon, Ariana Grande takes on the role of a zebra, and Ed Sheeran plays a koala bear.

Dave went on to describe the meaning of this song on The Ellen Show by saying:

I mean honestly when I started making this song I didn’t know the details or the facts at hand. But like we have 12 years to change the way we do so many things on earth, or the damage is irreversible. And within our lifetime, well within our lifetime, crazy things are gonna happen. Floods, food shortages, bad air, millions of people relocated… It’s like… very soon.

It was also announced that proceeds from this song and video will be going towards the Leonardo DiCaprio Foundation, which fights to help protect vulnerable wildlife from extinction.

“$ave Dat Money” is the first single from Lil Dicky’s debut studio album Professional Rapper. He collabs with summer star Fetty Wap on the hook and a short interlude by Rich Homie Quan to make a song unlike all other rap songs: saving money instead of blowing it all.

It’s interesting to note that both features and the producer, Money Alwayz, have artist names that revolve around the concept of wealth.

The song gained popularity when the music video (which cost $0 to make) was released. Celebrities such as T-Pain, Kevin Durant, Sarah Silverman, Hannibal Buress, and Mark Cuban were featured. The music video also featured mansions and houses that were acquired by going door to door in Beverly Hills and borrowing each item for 15 minutes​. Not only did Lil Dicky not spend any money in filming, but he actually made $600 in product placement.

description.plain:
“Professional Rapper” is the second track off of Lil Dicky’s debut album Professional Rapper. This track is structured like a job interview with Snoop acting as the interviewer and Dicky as the prospective employee. Dicky, having come from a non-traditional background in-terms of the rap game is espousing his skills, goals, and desires just like any other job interview; but the job in question is “Professional Rapper.”

Snoop, being one of the rap game’s most well-known and veteran rappers, embodies not only the interviewer but the hip-hop community as well, being skeptical of a new white comedy rapper. By trying to convince him, Dicky is also reaching out to this famously difficult community.

Take reference to the cover of this album, which show’s Mr. Burd’s resume. It is clear that he is trying to make the transition from copywriter/marketing whiz to professional rapper.

description.plain:
“Pillow Talking” is the 13th song on Lil Dicky’s debut album, Professional Rapper. It also happens to be his favorite song on the album.



The song details the conversation between Lil Dicky and a one night stand after having sex. The conversation covers a wide range of topics from the sex, to the war, to God, to Uber, and more. The music video for pillow talking was a viral success and has 17 million views as of 2017. It was also the debut appearance of Lil Dicky’s alter ego “Brain” who now even has his own EP titled I’m Brain.

In an AMA Lil Dicky was asked if Pillow Talking was based on a real experience to which he replied—

So “Pillow Talking” isn’t based off of one single true story, but there are definitely a few different conversations I’ve had over the course of my single life… being in bed with a girl where I’ve just realized that we kind of philosophically differed. Uh, ‘cause you don’t… you… you’re just kind of sitting there after you have sex and you just talk and you end up learning a lot about the person. So it was based off of, I suppose, true experiences and conversations, but it wasn’t one single night gone wrong, the way the song is.

description.plain:
Here LD reflects on how his career has affected his relationships. He misses his ex-girlfriend Molly, and is aware of how easily she can find another relationship, which is a “hard pill to swallow” (an allusion to the drug “Molly,” also known as MDMA or ecstasy).

When asked by a fan via a Reddit AMA “Just how hard it was to make [the] decision [to breakup] and do you now think it was worth it?”, he replied:


It really wasn’t that difficult of a decision because I knew what had to be done. I knew that I had to pursue my dreams before anything. Going for music wasn’t something that I regret and it wasn’t something that I debated really. Me and Molly aren’t going to get married at this point, but even if it was my absolute soul mate, at the time I don’t think I would’ve been able to put her in front of me accomplishing my dreams.

So the decision wasn’t the difficult part. It was living with the realities of the outcome.


On that same AMA Dicky was asked how he got Urie to feature on the track, he stated:

He tweeted at me one time, and I replied back telling him I was a fan, and then I had this song that I thought he could sound good on (Molly). He came in the studio that week, and man oh man…was he the perfect guy for the song.

description.plain:
Professional Rapper’s second single sees LD focus on petty-crimes, crimes that many commit but few are ever punished by law. The song’s irony lies in rap’s mainstream ‘gangster’ culture where emcees rap about their crime-filled lifestyles and histories, whereas he plays on the suburban-white-juvenile rap-sheet.



Dicky makes some social commentary in this song. He is committing all of these crimes that range from not illegal, or hardly illegal (taking food to the cinema and stealing hotel shampoo) to speeding, statutory rape and drug consumption. Even though he is committing all these crimes, he is never getting in trouble. Given the current social climate (Ferguson, Eric Garner), Dicky is pointing out disparities in society, saying that all of what he does is okay because the crimes are menial compared to other illegal things. He is not endorsing white crime, but rather pointing out that they exist.

This song could be inspired by the twitter hashtag that was very popular; #CRIMINGWHILEWHITE, in which thousands of twitter users explained times when their white privilege got them out of punishment for crimes.

description.plain:
The first in a two part song titled ‘The Antagonist’ & ‘The Antagonist II’

Lil Dicky introduces his alter ego David Burd and spits bars, ironically his alter ego is his real identity. Lil Dicky, the joke rapper and David Burd, the one who wants to be a real rapper and stakeholder in the game. David explains his lack of haters and what motivates him to make rap. David’s antagonist is the tension between who he needs to be and who he wants to be. At one time fitting the ‘mold’ for media success and at the other maintaining his identity as an emerging artist.

Part II further explores this relationship within in more detail with a beat from your subconscious inner thought and his personalties battling it out.

description.plain:
“Truman” is the twentieth and final track on Lil Dicky’s 2015 studio album and Kickstarter fulfillment, Professional Rapper.

In this track, Lil Dicky draw parallels between his rap career and the “Truman Show,” starring Jim Carrey. Lil Dicky came onto the rap scene making comedic raps, which set the tone of the majority of his viewers' expectations. Lil Dicky has felt pressure from the viewers, much like Truman, to be a source of entertainment meeting these expectations. Just as Truman realizes there is more to life in the film, Lil Dicky knows he is capable of making a difference in rap. This album is his “ship crashing into the wall moment,” marking a new point in his career as a contender in rap.

description.plain:
The opening to Lil Dicky’s debut album, this interlude is an excerpt of a phone conversation he had with his mother (Jean) and father (Stewart) prior to this albums recording. This interlude introduces the listener to LD’s family, establishes their dynamic and his background.

The album hosts two other interludes, both excerpts from the same phone conversation. The conversation continues with:


Parental Advisory (Interlude)
Parent’s Still Don’t Understand (Interlude)



LD recorded this conversation without their knowledge, and they only allowed him to publish these interludes on the condition that he never recorded them again. There goes our hopes of a Burd Family Collaborative album.

description.plain:
“Earth” is an environmental awareness song, released three days before Earth Day in 2019, about the dangers that climate change has on our planet and its ecosystems.

During an interview on The Ellen Show, Lil Dicky revealed the track features over 30 artists, with each of them taking on the roles of a different animal. For example, Justin Bieber plays on the role of a baboon, Ariana Grande takes on the role of a zebra, and Ed Sheeran plays a koala bear.

Dave went on to describe the meaning of this song on The Ellen Show by saying:

I mean honestly when I started making this song I didn’t know the details or the facts at hand. But like we have 12 years to change the way we do so many things on earth, or the damage is irreversible. And within our lifetime, well within our lifetime, crazy things are gonna happen. Floods, food shortages, bad air, millions of people relocated… It’s like… very soon.

It was also announced that proceeds from this song and video will be going towards the Leonardo DiCaprio Foundation, which fights to help protect vulnerable wildlife from extinction.
